                 Tilera Source Distribution README

        Copyright 2013 Tilera Corporation.  All Rights Reserved.


Most Tilera packages are built natively from SRPMs, acquired from
CentOS 6.3 ("http://vault.centos.org/6.3/os/Source/SPackages/") or
EPEL ("http://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/6/SRPMS/").

These SRPMs can be rebuilt natively, using "/usr/bin/rpmbuild-tilera",
which will apply the Tilera-specific patches in "/usr/lib/rpm/tilera/".

To build SRPMs, you will first need to install several RPMs which are
not included in the small tile tarball, including autoconf, automake,
libtool, pkgconfig, redhat-rpm-config, and rpm-build, plus of course
any additional RPMs required by the SRPM which you are trying to build.

Note that the full tile tarball contains the result of installing all
of the RPMs built by Tilera (except the "debuginfo" RPMs).


Most other MDE components are built from sources in this directory.

Third-party packages are generally provided by "*.get" scripts, which,
when run in a given working directory, will download the open-source
tarball (or SRPM) for the particular package (if needed), extract it
into a source subdirectory with a similar name, and then apply the
patch that is contained in the "*.get" script.  The resulting sources
can usually be built by running "configure" and "make" (see below).

The remaining system sources are shipped in the "sys" directory:

 - sys/hv, the Tilera hypervisor
 - sys/bme, the Tilera Bare Metal Environment
 - sys/common_hvbme, code shared by "hv" and "bme"
 - sys/boot/makebootrom, the "tile-mkrom" program
 - sys/bogux, a sample minimal supervisor
 - sys/libc, support library used by hv and bogux
 - sys/libbz2, support library used by hv and bogux
 - sys/mpipe, mPIPE default classifier

The remaining user-level sources are shipped in the "tools" directory:

 - tools/gxcr, the Tilera MiCA library
 - tools/gxio, the Tilera gxio library
 - tools/gxpci, the Tilera TRIO library
 - tools/handy, a Tilera helper library
 - tools/manager, the Tilera monitor and shepherd
 - tools/mbootcli, a Tilera command line tool for mboot
 - tools/op2xml, a Tilera utility for processing OProfile sample data
 - tools/oprofile, the oprofile tool
 - tools/pci, some Tilera PCIe utilities
 - tools/perf2xml, a Tilera utility for processing Linux perf sample data
 - tools/thd, a minimal HTTP daemon for development/debug purposes
 - tools/tmc, the Tilera Multicore Components (TMC) library

Many of the tools are shipped under a dual license that allows
commercial use via the Tilera MDE License, or at your choice, the GNU
Lesser General Public License version 2.1.  The latter license is
shipped in this directory in the file COPYING.LIB.

To natively build the non-SRPM sources:

    You will need to install the basic tile tarball on your root
    filesystem, or export it via "tile-monitor --root".

    Note that this directory will be available as "/usr/tilera/src".

To cross-build the non-SRPM sources:

    In addition to a copy of the Tilera MDE, and a version of Linux which
    is supported by the MDE, you will need the following tools on your
    system to be able to build everything:

	Python (we use Python 2.5)
	A C++ compiler (the Makefiles are set up to use g++; we use
	    version 4.4.0)
	GNU make (we use version 3.81)
	doxygen (only if you want to use it to build docs; we use a
	   modified version of 1.5.7)

    We aren't aware of any strict dependencies on particular versions
    of the tools but we have not tested with versions other than those
    listed above.

    If you are cross-building on an x86 host platform, you must have
    the "TILERA_ROOT" variable set in your environment pointing to
    an appropriate installation subdirectory of the Tilera MDE before
    attempting to do any builds.  For example:

    $ eval `/opt/TileraMDE-4.0.0.123456/tilegx/bin/tile-env`

Build procedure:

  * To build a hypervisor, do the following in this directory:

	make -C sys

    The various generated hypervisor components will be written to sys/hv/;
    you can run tile-monitor with the --hv-bin-dir flag to boot using them.

  * To build a boot image, do the following in this directory:

	make -C sys bootrom

    The generated bootable image will be written to vmlinux.bootrom,
    and you can run tile-monitor with the --bootrom-file flag to boot it.
    (This is not recommended; typically you only need to build a boot
    image when you will be booting from SPI ROM.)

  * To build Doxygen documentation for the hypervisor source code, do
    the following:

	make -C sys/hv docs

    The generated documentation may be examined by pointing a browser
    at sys/hv/docs/html/index.html.

  * To build Linux, cd to a directory you wish to hold the source code
    and run the "linux-*.get" script from this directory to download,
    unpack, and patch the source code.  NOTE: There are two linux-*.get
    scripts; the older version is the baseline supported kernel, and the
    newer version is provided on an experimental, unsupported basis.

    Next, create an empty directory, "cd" into it, and run the
    "tile-prepare" script that was placed in the Linux source directory.
    This will set up the directory so you can run "make" to build Linux.
    You may also re-configure Linux prior to building, if you wish, for
    example by editing the ".config" file, or running "make menuconfig".

    Building Linux will create a "vmlinux" file, which you can
    reference by path in the tile-mkboot command to include in a
    bootrom file, or use as the secondary boot image for mboot.

  * To build Busybox, cd to a directory you wish to hold the source code
    and run the "busybox-*.get" script from this directory to download,
    unpack, and patch the source code.  Then create an empty directory,
    "cd" into it, and run the "tile-prepare" script that was placed
    in the Busybox source directory.

    This will set up the directory so you can run "make" to build
    Busybox.  You may also re-configure Busybox prior to building, if
    you wish, for example by editing the ".config" file, or running
    "make menuconfig".

    Building Busybox will create a "busybox" binary, which you can upload
    to a Tilera chip, or reference by path in a Linux contents.txt file.

  * To build an initramfs cpio archive to use with the Linux boot on
    a machine without persistent disk storage, choose a "contents"
    file (e.g. $TILERA_ROOT/tile/usr/lib/initramfs/default/contents.txt)
    and pass that as the first argument to tile-gen-initramfs.
    The second argument should be the name of the desired initramfs
    archive (typically ending in .cpio.gz).  You may copy the
    "default" directory and modify the contents to make your own.

  * To build an mboot bootrom from the shipped MDE contents, do:
    
    $TILERA_ROOT/bin/tile-mkboot --compress -o my-mboot.bootrom \
      vmlinux=$TILERA_ROOT/tile/boot/vmlinux_mboot \
      classifier=$TILERA_ROOT/tile/boot/classifier --hvc vmlinux.hvc

    If you want to modify the included Linux, you can build your own
    by starting from arch/tile/configs/${ARCH}_mbootconfig.  (See Linux
    build instructions above.)  You should copy the initramfs.cpio
    file that has the mboot userspace into the "usr" directory of the
    kernel build tree first.

    If you want to modify the standard initramfs contents, you can
    build your own by starting with
    $TILERA_ROOT/usr/lib/initramfs/mboot/contents.txt and the files
    in that directory.  (See initramfs build instructions above.)

    If you want to modify the included Busybox (shipped in
    $TILERA_ROOT/tile/usr/lib/mboot/busybox), you can build your own
    by starting from the Busybox mboot/tile-defconfig.  (See Busybox
    build instructions above.)

    If you modify the standard initramfs contents or any of its
    included files (such as busybox), you must rebuild the included
    Linux (as above) afterwards, since by default we embed the mboot
    initramfs in the mboot vmlinux, and note if you want to boot the
    mboot vmlinux using tile-monitor, you need to specify --no-initramfs
    to avoid loading the default initramfs file in the MDE.

  * To build Bogux, do the following:

	make -C sys/bogux

    A bootable image will be written to sys/bogux/bogux-sim.bootrom;
    you can use tile-monitor with the --bootrom-file flag to boot it.

  * To build the Bare Metal Environment (BME) library, do the following:

	make -C sys/libc && make -C sys/bme

    The resulting library will be written to sys/bme/libc.a.

  * To build gcc, cd to a directory you wish to hold the source code, and run
    the "gcc-4.4.*.get" script from this directory to download, unpack,
    and patch the source code.  Select and cd to a build directory,
    and run the configure script in the source directory with the
    following arguments:

    <path_to_src>/configure --prefix=<path>
    --enable-languages=<languages> --disable-bootstrap

    The "prefix" flag specifies the installation path ("/usr/local" is
    a decent choice).  The "enable-languages" flag specifies a comma
    separated list of languages to support.  The full list of
    languages supported are "c,c++,fortran,objc,obj-c++,java", from
    which you can select a subset.  The "disable-bootstrap" flag tells
    the compiler not to bootstrap itself.

    Then run "make -j16", and "make install".

    The same procedure applies if you want to install gcc 4.6, using
    the corresponding get script.

    Note that building gcc natively will require first installing the
    gmp-devel, mpfr-devel, flex, bison, and m4 RPMs.

  * To build glibc, cd to a directory you wish to hold the source code, and
    run the "glibc-2.12*.get" script from this directory to download,
    unpack, and patch the source code.  Select and cd to a build
    directory, and run the configure script natively in the source
    directory with the following arguments:

	<path_to_src>/configure --prefix=/usr --enable-static-nss \
	  --enable-add-ons=nptl,c_stubs,libidn \
	  --with-tls --with-__thread \
	  --disable-profile --enable-experimental-malloc \
	  CFLAGS="-fasynchronous-unwind-tables -DNDEBUG -g -O3"
	make

    The cross-build directions are somewhat more complex; see the
    Tilera open-source web page (http://www.tilera.com/scm/) for
    instructions on how to do it.

  * To build the Tilera Multicore Library, do the following:

        make -C tools/tmc

    The libtmc.a and libtmc.so.1 files will be built in tools/tmc.

    For information on separating the build from the source tree,
    see tools/tmc/Makefile.

  * To build newlib, cd to a directory you wish to hold the source code
    and run the "newlib-*.get" script from this directory to download,
    unpack, and patch the source code.  Then create an empty directory,
    "cd" into it, and run the "tile-prepare" script that was placed
    in the newlib source directory.

    This will set up the directory so you can run "make" to build
    newlib.  Building newlib will create libc.a, libm.a, and crt0.o
    that you can use to link against binaries built with -mnewlib.
    You may also build docs via "make -j1 dvi" in "lib[cm]/lib[cm].dvi".

Legal and support notes:

    This source code is distributed primarily for reference purposes;
    while we have provided a framework which allows you to build it, the
    generated binary images may not exactly match what Tilera distributes
    as part of our MDE product.  Because of this, Tilera cannot guarantee
    its correct operation, and to the extent any support is provided for
    problems encountered with this code it will be on a best-effort basis.

    Interfaces within the hypervisor, between the hypervisor and Linux, or
    between the hypervisor and Tilera's application programming libraries
    (such as gxio), are not committed product features and Tilera
    may change or eliminate any or all of them in any future MDE update;
    you rely upon them at your peril.

    References within this source code to potential future work or
    planned features are speculative, and Tilera explicitly disclaims
    any commitment to ever perform such work or deliver those features.
